objectType.description:
The IPLT priority to be assigned to outgoing
control frames.

The IPLT priority to be assigned to outgoing
OAM frames.

The MAC address of a remote network device that
claims prior ownership of one of the IP addresses
being used on the local node. See the notification
'tlsIpAddressConflict' for more information.

The IP address on the local node that has been
determined to be in conflict with another device
somewhere on the network. See the notification
'tlsIpAddressConflict' for more informaiton.

trunk group protocol stages.
Used by the tlsTrunkGroupErrorEvent trap.

trap is enabled or disabled.

ange
trap is enabled or disabled.

Provisioning information for all TD Connectivity
tests and each tests' results.

Provisioning information for a particular TD
Connectivity test and the test results.
The unique TDC test ID for this entry.
The customer TD on which this test is executed.

An index value that uniquely identifies the TLS
interface (UNI port) at the source of the test.

An index value that uniquely identifies the
destination TLS interface (LAN port).
The IP address of the source port or CPU.
The IP address of the destination port or CPU.

Optional 802.1 network priority to be used for
this test. If not specified by the user, the port
default priority is assumed.

Optional timeout period for the TDC test in seconds.
If not specified, a default value of 10 seconds will
be used.

The protocol to use for the TDC test. If not
specified by the user, the mode (protocol) of the
source UNI port will be assumed.

Optional target address of the TDC test. For tlsl2
protocol, the options are broadcast and unicast,
broadcast only and unicast only. For oel2 protocol,
the options are multicast and unicast, multicast only
and unicast only. By default, tlsl2 tests use broadcast
and unicast while oel2 tests use multicast and unicast.

Optional data associated with the TDC test. The
basic test validates the provisioning associated with
the source ports, destination ports and TDs configured
in the test. The time test collects the round-trip-time
of the packet between source and destination. The trace
test collects the IP address, machine adress and port
information for nodes along the source to destination
path (and back again). If not specified, the basic test
is assumed.

Boolean value indicating whether the user
specified the packet priority or not.
The number of test packets sent.
The number of test packets received.

The round-trip-time for a broadcast test packet in
microseconds.

The round-trip-time for a unicast test packet in
microseconds.

The OPE network priority. (ie. Customer priority
mapped into an OPE priority. Same as tlsTDPriorityMap.)
The local date stamp for the test (DD/MM).
The local time-of-day stamp for the test (HH:MM:SS).

Boolean value indicating whether the trace info
exists for this entry.
Used to create/delete an entry in this table
Initiate this TDC test.
Result from the last TDC action

The error mask associated with the TDC test. Each bit
in the mask represents a specific error. The errors
from least significant bit to highest significant bit
are:
bit 1 - TD nonexistent on destination port
bit 2 - TD disabled on destination port
bit 3 - TD not assigned to destination port
bit 4 - TD filtered on destination NNI port
bit 5 - destination port is NNI
bit 6 - destination port is craft
bit 7 - destination FDB test failed
bit 8 - destination administrative state down
bit 9 - destination operational state down
bit 10 - destination port connectivity mismatch error
bit 11 - destination port type mismatch
bit 12 - destination port mode mismatch error
bit 13 - destination MIB query failed
bit 14 - destination system error
bit 15 - invalid destination port
bit 16 - destination port is CPU
bit 17 - destination port mode mismatch warning
bit 18 - destination port connectivity mismatch warning
bit 19 - default priority used on destination
bit 20 - IP not assigned on destination oel2 port
bit 21 - static entry exists on destination port
bit 22 - destination FDB table full warning
bit 33 - TD nonexistent on source port
bit 34 - TD not assigned to source port
bit 35 - source FDB test failed
bit 36 - source administrative state down
bit 37 - source operational state down
bit 38 - source system error
bit 39 - no response
bit 40 - could not get trace information
bit 41 - could not get time information
bit 42 - source MIB query failed
bit 43 - TD disabled on source port
bit 44 - invalid source port
bit 45 - all ports down on the source node
bit 46 - unknown error
bit 47 - source FDB test failed
bit 48 - static entry exists on source port
bit 49 - no FDB entry for destination MAC, unicast aborted
Trace information for a TD Connectivity test.

Trace information for the last TD Connectivity test
that had the trace functionality enabled.

The unique TDC test ID to which these results
correspond.

Type of TDC test packet for which these results
apply.

The trace sequence number associated with this
entry.

The MAC address of the node by which this sequence
entry was generated.

The IP address of the node by which this sequence
entry was generated.

The port number on which this node sent the outbound
test packet.

The port number on which this node received the
inbound test packet.
Number of trunk groups currently defined on the card.
Number of trunk groups currently defined on the ring.

Table containing provisioning and status information
pertaining to all trunk groups defined on this OPE card.

Provisioning and status information pertaining to
a particular trunk group.

A value that uniquely identifies the trunk group on
the ring.

A text string providing further information about
the trunk group.

A user assigned identifier that is used to distribute
traffic between the two redundant trunks. The range of
this identifier comes from a result of a load-sharing
algorithm applied to all frames forwarded by trunks in
a trunk group. Frames whose hash result is 0 will be
forwarded by trunk with traffic ditribution id of 0.
Frames with result 1 will be forwarded by trunk with
ditribution id of 1. The value of 0/1 can be provisioned.
The value of 2 can not be provisioned. Each trunk in a
trunk group must have a unique distribution id.

A system assigned distribution id that is defaulted to
by the system in the case of the user assigned distribution
ids mismatch. The distribution ids
of the two trunks are mismatched if both of them
have the same value. The system then assigns distribution
id of 1 to a trunk with a higher MAC address and 0 to
trunk with a lower MAC address.
The system assigned distribution ids default to the user
assigned distribution ids if the user assigned distribution
ids are unique for both of the trunks in the trunk group.
Enables a specific trunk group on the ring.

The trunk Mac address. The trunk Mac address is not
provisionable at this time.
The trunk Mac address is the Mac address of the port
that is a member of this trunk.

The type of the trunk group. Only type 'dmlt' is
supported at this time. This field is not
provisionable at this time.

The type of the port: nni, uni mapped, uni transparent.
Only type nni is supported at this time. This field is not
provisionable at this time.

The list of ports defined on this card that belong to
this trunk. A trunk consists of only one port at this time.

The Wait To Restore timer in seconds. Only the value of
5 seconds is supported at this time. This field is not
provisionable at this time.
The operational state of the trunk group.

The type of distribution algorithm used by this trunk
group. To be used in the future. This field is not
provisionable at this time.
Used to create/delete an entry.

port member Mac address at this time.

by the system in the case of the user assigned distribution

of the two trunks are mismatched if both of them
